        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[Feature]: Channel Broker Phase 2A conformance harness",
        "body": "## Maintainer TL;DR\n\nThis stack consolidates the recurring Telegram/Discord/Slack/WhatsApp/Signal/iMessage/etc. maintenance churn behind one Channel Broker contract. OpenClaw keeps the shared semantics that repeatedly regress across native channel plugins: sessions, allowlists, routing, /verbose, streaming policy, durable final sends, receipts, retries, and auditability. Broker providers own platform mechanics: bot APIs, bridge/device state, native ids, delivery quirks, and provider capabilities.\n\nThis PR is the regression shield. It turns the recurring channel pain into shared conformance: signed inbound webhooks, normalization, dedupe, durable final sends, receipts, retryable failures, preview/progress gates, and /verbose channelData.\n\nThe direction is intentionally incremental: first land the versioned broker SDK/plugin foundation, then prove conformance, then prove opt-in routing for the major channels, then model long-tail and constrained providers. Only after migration paths exist should legacy native-channel feature work freeze in #86115.\n\n## Why This Is Better\n\nToday, one fix to streaming, /verbose, or delivery behavior can make Telegram fast this week and then break Discord, Slack, or another native plugin the next week. The broker path makes those shared semantics one OpenClaw-owned contract instead of many platform-specific re-implementations. When a provider adds support for previews, threads, receipts, media, or constrained account modes, that capability can become available through the same contract to routed channels whose provider declares and passes conformance for it.\n\n## Stack Shape\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n  U[\"Umbrella issue #86105: reduce maintained-channel churn\"] --> P1[\"#86096 Phase 1: SDK + bundled broker foundation\"]\n  P1 --> P2A[\"#86153 Phase 2A: conformance + signed inbound\"]\n  P2A --> P2B[\"#86154 Phase 2B: Telegram opt-in proof\"]\n  P2B --> P2C[\"#86156 Phase 2C: Discord opt-in proof\"]\n  P2C --> P2D[\"#86157 Phase 2D: Slack opt-in proof\"]\n  P2D --> P3[\"#86164 Phase 3: official/app capability matrix\"]\n  P3 --> P4[\"#86165 Phase 4: constrained provider capabilities\"]\n  P4 -. \"future, not in this stack\" .-> P5[\"Future freeze issue #86115: legacy native-plugin freeze\"]\n```\n\n| PR | Role in the consolidation |\n| --- | --- |\n| #86096 | Creates the versioned broker SDK/plugin foundation, provider routing guard, media final-send mapping, SecretRef/cancellation handling, and prefix-ownership contract. |\n| #86153 | Proves shared lifecycle conformance and adds signed inbound webhook registration/runtime handoff: inbound dedupe, durable final sends, receipts, retryable failures, preview/progress gates, and /verbose channelData. |\n| #86154 | Proves Telegram topics can route through broker targets without native Telegram internals. |\n| #86156 | Proves Discord DMs/channels/threads preserve conversation semantics through broker routing. |\n| #86157 | Proves Slack DMs/channel threads preserve direct/thread semantics through broker routing. |\n| #86164 | Adds official/app platform aliases, capability matrix rows, and declared delivery capability enforcement for long-tail channels. |\n| #86165 | Adds constrained-provider metadata for WhatsApp, Signal, iMessage, and bridge-backed providers. |\n\n## Ownership Model\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  Core[\"OpenClaw core<br/>sessions, routing, allowlists<br/>/verbose, streaming, retries<br/>receipts, audit\"] --> Broker[\"channel-broker plugin<br/>openclaw/plugin-sdk/channel-broker<br/>V1 protocol\"]\n  Broker --> Provider[\"Provider-owned broker<br/>HTTP/webhook transport<br/>platform adapters\"]\n  Provider --> Platforms[\"Telegram, Discord, Slack<br/>Teams, Matrix, WhatsApp<br/>Signal, iMessage, long tail\"]\n  Provider --> Broker\n  Broker --> Core\n```\n\n## Review Shape\n\nThese PRs are intentionally linear. GitHub still shows `main` as the base for each PR so maintainers can land them one by one from fork branches; the branches themselves are stacked, and maintainers can review the focused adjacent diffs here:\n\n| PR | Focused adjacent diff |\n| --- | --- |\n| #86153 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-protocol...feat/channel-broker-conformance |\n| #86154 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-conformance...feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing |\n| #86156 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing...feat/channel-broker-discord-routing |\n| #86157 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-discord-routing...feat/channel-broker-slack-routing |\n| #86164 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-slack-routing...feat/channel-broker-official-platform-capabilities |\n| #86165 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-official-platform-capabilities...feat/channel-broker-constrained-platform-capabilities |\n\n## This PR\n\n- Phase: Phase 2A - Conformance and signed inbound baseline\n- Role: Proves shared lifecycle conformance and adds signed inbound webhook registration/runtime handoff.\n- Head: `0e3959978e`\n\n## Current Review State\n\nThis PR is live for maintainer review. Current head: `0e3959978e`.\n\nFocused local validation for this phase is documented below. Broad validation remains owned by GitHub Actions. Native channel defaults remain unchanged unless this phase explicitly says otherwise.\n\n## Summary\n\n- Adds the Phase 2A Channel Broker conformance baseline on top of #86096.\n- Extends `openclaw/plugin-sdk/channel-broker` with inbound normalization, dedupe-key, provider capability normalization, and platform capability checks.\n- Adds bundled broker conformance coverage for durable inbound receive, durable final send receipts, retryable receipt failures, preview/progress capability gates, and `/verbose`/tool-message `channelData`.\n\n## Rollout Context\n\nCloses #86109\nRelated #86108\nRelated #86105\nStacked on #86096\nSupersedes closed PR #86133, which was closed by the repository active-PR cap rather than by an implementation failure.\n\nThis PR intentionally does not migrate Telegram, Discord, or Slack routing. Native defaults stay unchanged until the Phase 2B/2C/2D proofs land behind opt-in broker routing.\n\nFor review, the focused stack diff is:\nhttps://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-protocol...feat/channel-broker-conformance\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** The broker conformance baseline normalizes inbound events, builds durable dedupe keys, evaluates preview/progress capabilities, and sends outbound requests through the bundled broker lifecycle without platform-specific core branches.\n- **Real environment tested:** Local OpenClaw checkout at `/Volumes/LEXAR/repos/openclaw-channel-broker`, using the Channel Broker plugin and SDK from the stacked rollout branch on May 24, 2026.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Ran a `node --import tsx --input-type=module` terminal proof that imported `src/plugin-sdk/channel-broker.ts`, created a Telegram inbound event, built the durable dedupe key, evaluated Discord preview/progress capabilities, and sent broker outbound requests through `channelBrokerPlugin.message.send.text`.\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal output excerpt from that local command:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"inboundDedupeKey\": \"acme:bot-main:telegram:live-proof-telegram-1\",\n  \"previewProgressSupported\": true\n}\n```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** The live SDK/plugin path produced the expected durable inbound key and capability decision outside the Vitest harness, proving the Phase 2A contract surface can carry the normalized lifecycle facts that later channel migrations consume.\n- **What was not tested:** Live provider network traffic and the full local suite; those remain covered by later provider proofs and GitHub Actions.\n\n### Behavior\n\nThe broker contract now has a conformance harness for the lifecycle paths that regress most often across maintained chat channels: inbound normalization/dedupe, durable final sends, provider receipts, retry/failure propagation, preview/progress capability checks, and `/verbose` tool-message metadata.\n\n### Environment\n\n- Local checkout: `/Volumes/LEXAR/repos/openclaw-channel-broker`\n- Branch: `feat/channel-broker-conformance`\n- Head: `0e3959978e` (current Phase 2A head)\n\n### Steps\n\n1. Normalized a synthetic Telegram inbound event through the SDK and accepted it through the durable inbound receive journal.\n2. Replayed the same dedupe key while pending and after completion to prove duplicate/redelivery handling.\n3. Sent a synthetic Slack final message through the bundled broker runtime and verified provider receipt commit material.\n4. Returned a retryable Discord provider receipt and verified the send fails with structured receipt context.\n5. Built preview/finalize broker requests and asserted Discord preview/progress support through declared capabilities.\n6. Passed `/verbose` tool-message policy through broker `channelData` without platform-specific branching.\n\n### Evidence\n\n- `OPENCLAW_VITEST_INCLUDE_FILE=/Volumes/LEXAR/Codex/channel-broker-vitest-include.json pnpm exec vitest run --config test/vitest/vitest.unit-fast.config.ts`\n  - 1 file passed, 7 tests passed.\n- `pnpm exec vitest run extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.test.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/conformance.test.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/secret-contract.test.ts --config test/vitest/vitest.extension-channel-broker.config.ts`\n  - 3 files passed, 10 tests passed.\n- `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit -p extensions/channel-broker/tsconfig.json`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm tsgo:core:test`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check src/plugin-sdk/channel-broker.ts src/plugin-sdk/channel-broker.test.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/outbound.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/conformance.test.ts`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm exec oxlint extensions/channel-broker --format unix`\n  - passed.\n- `git diff --check`\n  - passed.\n\n### Observed Result\n\nThe SDK helpers normalize provider payloads without dropping native metadata, the bundled plugin refuses non-sent provider receipts as durable-send failures, and conformance tests prove the current broker path can represent the Phase 2 lifecycle requirements without changing user-visible channel defaults.\n\n### Not Tested\n\n- Full local suite. Per `/Volumes/LEXAR` policy, broad validation is left to GitHub Actions.\n- Live Telegram, Discord, or Slack provider traffic. Those are intentionally scoped to Phase 2B/2C/2D.\n\n## Current Stack Gate Context\n\nThis branch is rebased on the current Phase 1 foundation head. Focused local validation is documented above or below; broad validation remains on GitHub Actions.\n\n",
